@NODE Distribution "Distribution"
    
    The following is NOT a bunch of restrictions, so please read it!
    
    Through the  years,  many  concepts  have  been  constructed  to  make
    programmers of various software both  famous and rich. The problem  is
    that most users seem to  "over-look" copyright notices and prayers  in
    the manuals for both commercial and Public Domain software. Even  more
    obvious things  like guilt-requesters  that pops  up all  the time  to
    remind people to send money are mostly ignored or even removed.
    
    Keeping the above in  mind we don't expect to  get any rich by  making
    SaveTime and we will  therefore NOT ask any  money for SaveTime -  not
    now  and  not  ever.  Basically  we  made  SaveTime  for  the  fun  of
    programming. However, we have spent  many hours on getting  everything
    to work, on testing, on writing  this manual, on drawing icons and  on
    getting new  ideas.  Therefore we  would  like  to know  if  you  like
    SaveTime; and if you don't, what we must do to make you like it.
    
    Therefore the only thing we request is a small letter telling us  what
    you like  and what  you  dislike, which  bugs  you've found  and  what
    suggestions you have. You can  either send the letter through  regular
    mail or as a NetMail (if you have access to FidoNet) and you can  rest
    assured that we'll  appreciate it. It's  not like we  get tons of  fan
    mail so  we'll  even have  the  time to  respond  to your  letter  and
    probably even  mail you  a  new version  of  SaveTime if/when  one  is
    released.
    
    For our address: Read the @{" authors " Link authors} section.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE What's_SaveTime? "What's SaveTime?"
    
    SaveTime is a software based battery  backed up clock. If you  install
    it, your  clock will  not be  set to  some weird  value if  the  Amiga
    crashes or you turn  it off. The time will  just stand still. This  is
    useful if  you haven't  got a  real battery  backed up  clock and  use
    utilities that depends on  the clock or the  date stamp of your  files
    (e.g. Reminder or DMake).
    
    You won't get  a clock that's  precise down to  the last micro  second
    (though, with  various  new  options,  much  more  precise  than  with
    previous versions of SaveTime). Furthermore  the clock will only  work
    when SaveTime is installed  - you might call  SaveTime the battery  to
    your fake clock (there are, however,  options to make up for the  time
    when SaveTime isn't running).
    
    If you turn your Amiga off for a longer period of time (like when  you
    sleep, whenever you prefer to do that), it would be a good idea to set
    the time by  hand when the  Amiga is turned  on again; otherwise  your
    clock will be several hours behind.  Though this fact will not  bother
    stupid DMake, as long as the  chronology of the date stamps is  right,
    it might bother you, and Reminder will remind you of events a  sleep's
    length too late.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE What's_new_in_version_2.40? "What's new in version 2.40?"
    
    SaveTime 2.40  is mainly  a maintenance  update. That  is, the  basics
    haven't changed much, but it's more comfortable to use. You could also
    say that it can't do much more than  version 2.31 but it does it in  a
    friendlier way. The improvements include:
         
         SaveTime doesn't detach from the Shell anymore (unsafe idea).
         
         Better handling of the @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} window
           - Gadgets auto repeat and passing midnight flips the date.
           - Asyncronous.
           - Will pop up on ^D signal (used by @{" SaveTimePrefs " Link SaveTimePrefs}).
         
         Workbench support.
         
         Extended Shell help.
         
         Preferences program/@{" settings file " Link settings_file} (Kickstart 2.0+ only).
         
         @{" Installer " Link Installer} script included.
         
         This manual is now in .guide format.
         
         The source is cleaned up; potential bugs removed.
    
    As we don't just polish up an  old product, we HAVE added a great  new
    thing in  version 2.40;  the @{" RESETHANDLER " Link RESETHANDLER}  option. If  you have  the
    right equipment this can give you  a slightly more precise clock  (the
    right equipment is a keyboard that supports the reset handler stuff).
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installing_SaveTime "Installing SaveTime"

    The supplied @{" Installer " Link Installer}  script should take  care of the  installing,
    but in  case you  haven't got  Installer  or if  you prefer  a  manual
    installation (it's not that  hard), here are  "some" useful notes.  My
    suggestion is that  you try with  Installer first, and  if it  doesn't
    work then consult this chapter again...
    
@{" Requirements " Link Requirements}
@{" Letting Shell start SaveTime " Link Letting_Shell_start_SaveTime}
@{" Letting Workbench start SaveTime " Link Letting_Workbench_start_SaveTime}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "Requirements"
    
    SaveTime does not require any  external programs and does not  require
    loads of memory neither (less than 20KB). This is, unfortunately, true
    for Kickstart 2.0+ operation only.
    
    If you use Kickstart  1.3 (or perhaps even  1.2?), then you WILL  need
    the @{" arp.library " Link arp.library} in your  @{" LIBS " Link LIBS} drawer as well  as possibly the  Run
    command in your C: drawer (they are either in ROM or not needed if you
    use Kickstart 2.0+).  The Run  command should  only be  needed if  you
    intend to start SaveTime from the Shell and may be replaced by RunBack
    or other similar programs.
    
    SaveTime is meant to be started automatically every time you boot  the
    Amiga. It is  hereby suggested that  you let either  the Shell or  the
    Workbench start SaveTime  (depending on what  environment you  usually
    work in) as doing  it yourself pretty much  eliminates the benefit  of
    SaveTime - then you could as well set the time on every reboot.
    
    If you prefer the Shell: @{" Letting Shell start SaveTime " Link Letting_Shell_start_SaveTime}
    If you prefer Workbench: @{" Letting Workbench start SaveTime " Link Letting_Workbench_start_SaveTime}
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Letting_Shell_start_SaveTime "Letting Shell start SaveTime"
    
    For SaveTime to get executed every time you boot, you'll have to put a
    line in your s:user-startup. If you  have no idea of what  the s:user-
    startup file is or don't know how to edit it, we suggest that you skip
    to the next section, @{" Letting Workbench start SaveTime " Link Letting_Workbench_start_SaveTime}.
    If you  haven't  got  Kickstart 2.0+  you  will  not be  able  to  let
    Workbench start SaveTime and then you either need to collect some help
    from your  friends  or  buy  a Kickstart  2.0+  (the  latter  is  more
    expensive but better :-).
    
    What you need  to put in  s:user-startup is simply  a line  containing
    'Run SaveTime' plus whatever @{" arguments " Link arguments} you might want. For example:
    
    Run SaveTime FILE S:Time DELAY 30 ADDSECS 8 RESETHANDLER 2
    
    If you use @{" settings  file " Link settings__file} (possible with  Kickstart 2.0+ only)  then
    you can leave it at 'Run SaveTime'.
    
    The way  you enter  arguments  is quite  simple:  you just  enter  the
    keyword (like  'FILE' and  'DELAY' and  so on  in the  above  example)
    followed by a space and then the actual argument value (just like tool
    types for the Workbench, only these are entered as a vertical list and
    has an equal sign between the keyword and the value). If the  argument
    is a switch  (currently only 'QUIT')  you just type  that and  nothing
    more.
    
    To get a list  of all the  valid arguments you  can start SaveTime  by
    using the  argument '?'  - that  is, type  'SaveTime ?'  at the  Shell
    prompt. This will display the syntax of SaveTime in standard  AmigaDos
    format. Pressing '?' here will  show a more understandable text.  Once
    you figure out  what arguments you  need you can  enter them  straight
    away -  SaveTime  is  waiting for  you  to  enter them  after  it  has
    displayed either the AmigaDos syntax or the extended help.
    
    SaveTime runs safely with a stack of just 3000 bytes, so you can  gain
    a little RAM  by inserting  a 'Stack  3000' command  right before  the
    SaveTime line. This is not nessecary and is only advised if you happen
    to know what the stack actually is. (A smaller stack might work but is
    untested).
    
    Oh yeah -  of course you  should also copy  SaveTime to somewhere  the
    Shell can find it. If you can't think of anywhere else, then try  'C:'
    (use 'Copy SaveTime TO C:').
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Letting_Workbench_start_SaveTime "Letting Workbench start SaveTime"
    
    First of all: The following is only possible if you're using Workbench
    2.0 or above. Once  you've got that Workbench,  you'll simply have  to
    drag the SaveTime  icon into  the drawer on  your boot  disk which  is
    called 'WBStartup'. As  long as  SaveTime is  kept here,  it will  get
    executed whenever the Workbench is started.
    
    The following  is possible  with all  Workbenches, though  the  layout
    described is  the one  of Workbench  2.0. It's  not of  much use  with
    Workbench 1.3 anyway,  however, as  you need  to double  click on  the
    SaveTime icon yourself every time you want to start it. Shell usage is
    actually the thing to go for if you use Kickstart 1.3.
    
    You pass @{" arguments " Link arguments} to  SaveTime via Workbench  by using tool  types,
    which is also  rather simple: single  click on the  SaveTime icon  and
    select 'Information' from the 'Icons' menu (these names may of  course
    vary if you  use a  localized Workbench). This  will pop  up a  window
    which, in the bottom,  contains a list  of the tool  types. To edit  a
    tool type, just click on it and edit it in the string gadget. To add a
    new, click on 'New' and type it in the same string gadget. To remove a
    tool type you can click first on the tool type and then on 'Del'.
    
    You enter a tool type as 'ARGUMENTNAME=ARGUMENTVALUE'. That is, if you
    want to specify where  SaveTime should put it's  data file, you  could
    for example enter a tool type as 'FILE=HARDDISK:SavedTime'. This  will
    make SaveTime use the file 'HARDDISK:SavedTime' as its data file.
    
    PLEASE NOTE: You should never remove the tool type called 'DONOTWAIT'.
    If you leave  this tool  type out and  put SaveTime  in the  WBStartup
    drawer the Workbench will be forced to wait until SaveTime is finished
    before it  will  proceed with  its  initialisation. Needless  to  say,
    SaveTime will  NOT  quit  in  any  foreseeable  future  and  thus  the
    Workbench will never proceed. Having  the 'DONOTWAIT' while not  using
    the WBStartup drawer does no harm, so better leave it in!
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Arguments "Arguments"
    
    The way SaveTime  does its  job can be  slightly altered  by means  of
    arguments. This way you  can get SaveTime to  fit as good as  possible
    into your environment.
    
    To learn  how to  enter  arguments, please  read  one of  these  parts
    (depending on how you start SaveTime):
    @{" Letting Workbench start SaveTime " Link Letting_Workbench_start_SaveTime}
    @{" Letting Shell start SaveTime " Link Letting_Shell_start_SaveTime}
    @{" SaveTimePrefs " Link SaveTimePrefs} (Suggested!)
    
    The following arguments are currently supported by SaveTime:
    
@{" FILE " Link FILE}
@{" DELAY " Link DELAY}
@{" ADDSECS " Link ADDSECS}
@{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME}
@{" RESETHANDLER " Link RESETHANDLER}
@{" QUIT " Link QUIT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE FILE "FILE"
    
    The FILE argument specifies where SaveTime should put (and get :-) its
    datafile (which contains  nothing but  what time it  was written).  As
    SaveTime is not a  true battery backed  up clock it  needs a place  to
    store what  the  time actually  is.  This  is then  loaded  back  when
    SaveTime is started again (usually after a reboot).
    
    The default is 'S:SavedTime'.
    
    Don't specify FILE  to be on  a RAM-disk unless  it's recoverable,  as
    this  would ruin the idea of  SaveTime - once you reboot, the time  is
    lost; and that's just when you need it.
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE DELAY "DELAY"
    
    DELAY defines the length of  the loop SaveTime performs, specified  in
    seconds. Default is 60. A small  value will give a more precise  clock
    but also a  more busy system.  A high value  will, of course,  reverse
    both. Guess that 60 is an okay choice.
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE ADDSECS "ADDSECS"
    
    ADDSECS is the  number of  seconds that  SaveTime should  add when  it
    first sets the system time. To figure out how large this value  should
    be, simply  try to  reboot  (after you've  installed SaveTime  in  the
    s:user-sequence or in  the WBStartup  drawer) and check  out how  many
    seconds the clock lost.
    This is the value you should use (± ˝·DELAY - unless you're using  the
    RESETHANDLER option). By time you'll figure out if the value should be
    adjusted (e.g. if the  clock is always behind  this value should be  a
    little bigger).
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE SETTIME "SETTIME"
    
    Specifying the  SETTIME argument  will make  SaveTime open  a  window,
    containing the  date and  time it  believes it  is (the  time will  be
    running). This is displayed as Day-Month-Year Hour:Minute:Second.
    
    The number you specify  after SETTIME is how  many seconds the  window
    should stay  open. If,  after  this time,  you  haven't clicked  in  a
    gadget, SaveTime will close the window  by itself. However, if you  DO
    click before the window  closes, then the time  will stop running  (so
    you won't get confused, trying to  set it properly) and you will  have
    to close the window yourself (using the close gadget of the window).
    
    You can use the arrow gadgets to click towards the time it really  is,
    or you  can  click directly  on  the  numbers; this  will  activate  a
    'hidden' text gadget, and  you can enter the  time using the  keyboard
    which is often quicker (if the time is much wrong).
    
    When you close  the window, the  internal clock (that  is not  battery
    backed up) is set to the  entered value, unless it is entered  wrongly
    in which case  no setting  will happen.  If you  enter the  time in  a
    format that  is different  from the  one that  pops up,  it will  most
    likely not be understood.
    
@{" Re-opening the SETTIME window " Link Re-opening_the_SETTIME_window}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Re-opening_the_SETTIME_window "Re-opening the SETTIME window"
    
    If you should want to set the time while SaveTime is already  running,
    you can open the SETTIME window  by sending the running SaveTime a  ^D
    signal (if you don't know about ^D then don't mind). There are several
    ways to do this.  From the Workbench  the only choice  is to open  the
    SaveTimePrefs program  and  click  in  the  'Set  time'  gadget.  This
    approach also works like a beauty  with the Shell, so I advise you  to
    use it.
    
    Note two things here: a) you can always open the SETTIME window,  even
    if you didn't specify the SETTIME argument in the first place. And  b)
    the window will not go away by itself if you open it using ^D (like it
    does when you use the SETTIME argument). Therefore you must close  the
    window yourself.
    
    If you should happen to  know another way to  send a ^D signal to  the
    SaveTime process then you  can use that. I  will not give you  further
    instructions on this issue as SaveTimePrefs is all you need.
    
    (The following is not to be considered as being serious talk - but  it
    does indeed work).
    Whoops, I just came to think  that the SaveTimePrefs idea is not  that
    bright if you use Kickstart 1.3  (SaveTimePrefs is for 2.0+ only),  so
    here's what you can do: write a little program that does the following
    and you should do fine again:
    
    if (FindPort("SaveTime"))
           Signal(FindPort("SaveTime")->mp_SigTask, SIGBREAKF_CTRL_D);
    
    (Hmm; perhaps this program should follow SaveTime or get incoorporated
    into SaveTime itself... look out for version 2.50 :-).
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE RESETHANDLER "RESETHANDLER"
    
    The RESETHANDLER is a very nice feature. If you use this feature, then
    a so called reset handler will  get installed. This handler will  save
    the data file  AFTER you've  pressed Ctrl-A-A. This  is great,  simply
    because the clock will not loose the time that has passed by from  the
    last save and until the reset was performed. You'll get a more precise
    clock because you don't  have to find an  average value in  @{" ADDSECS " Link ADDSECS},
    but you can use an exact.
    The argument that this option requires  is the number of seconds  that
    SaveTime will halt the  reset procedure after  writing the data  file.
    This value should be as little as possible, but still allow your  file
    system to  update  everything  correct  (a  floppy  requires  about  5
    seconds, for example).  The problem is  that you only  knows for  sure
    that the value is too low  when you've corrupted your disk.  Therefore
    you should time  how long it  normally takes to  write the data  file.
    Note that after writing  the file, the Amiga  will wait a little  time
    (around half a second on my harddisk) and then write again. This is to
    update the file system  after the write. The  time you specify  should
    include all this writing and probably  another second to be safe.  The
    Amiga will perform the reset after 10 seconds or so (slightly keyboard
    dependant), even if you enter a higher value.
    
    A few notes on this option: 
    
    1. The reset procedure will last  a little longer than usual. This  is
    because of the time SaveTime waits after the writing of the data file.
    During this time you can still  operate the Amiga - only the  keyboard
    has already been reset, so you can't type anything.
    
    2. The reset handler will only  get activated if you use the  keyboard
    to reset the  Amiga. If  you get  a 'Software  Failure' requester,  it
    would therefore  be wiser  to reboot  by hand,  instead of  using  the
    'Reboot' gadget. You can  of course also 'Suspend'  and then reset  by
    hand later. This is all because the reset handler is controlled by the
    little chip handling the keyboard.
    
    3. This feature  is unfortunately  not available to  all (actually  to
    quite few). It requires the right keyboard, as that part of the  reset
    procedure is handled  by the keyboard.  Some keyboards doesn't  signal
    the Amiga so it can signal  SaveTime when the reset is performed  :-(.
    Commodore has said that:
    
    "Few of the  Amiga keyboard  models generate  the communication  codes
    used to implement this reset  processing.  Specificaly, only the  Euro
    a1000 (rare), and the B2000 keyboard generate them."
    
    This is not true  (any longer). We have  successfully tested it on  an
    Amiga 1200 (which was  not out when the  quoted text was written).  As
    other models may  therefore also  prove success, we  suggest that  you
    just try out if it works for  you (by checking if the drive lights  up
    just when you reboot  and the reboot procedure  lasts a little  longer
    than usually)!
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE QUIT "QUIT"
    
    This argument is only valid when  SaveTime is started from the  Shell.
    When specified, it will send a request to an already running  SaveTime
    to ask it to quit.
    If SaveTime  is started  (from  Workbench or  the Shell)  and  another
    SaveTime is  already running,  a much  similar effect  will happen:  a
    requester pops up, asking if you want to signal the other SaveTime  to
    quit (the newly invoked SaveTime will  always quit - you can only  run
    SaveTime once at a time).
    For further information on terminating SaveTime, see @{" how to quit " Link how_to_quit}.
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE How_SaveTime_works "How SaveTime works"
    
    The following is a description of  what SaveTime performs, once it  is
    run.
    
    First of all SaveTime gets its default arguments from the file  called
    'ENVARC:SaveTime.prefs'  (only  with  Kickstart  2.0+,  however)   and
    thereafter reads the specified arguments. If SaveTime is run from  the
    Workbench the tool types  will be checked for  arguments, if run  from
    Shell the command line arguments are checked.
    
    Then SaveTime checks if it has  already been run before. If a  running
    SaveTime is found, the newly run informs you and asks you if you  want
    to send  a break  signal to  the running  SaveTime. This  is really  a
    question of whether  you want  to kill one  or two  SaveTime's as  the
    newly invoked will stop no matter  what you decide to do with the  one
    that is already running.
    
    Now the reset handler and the @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} window are opened (only if the
    arguments enabling  them  are specified,  of  course). The  time  that
    SaveTime saved in a file last time it was run is read in and the clock
    of the Amiga is set to that time.
    
    SaveTime will then run in an infinitive loop, where it will first wait
    for some time (specified by the  @{" DELAY " Link DELAY} argument) and then write  the
    time to the datafile. It will  only terminate the loop if you asks  it
    to quit (see @{" How to quit " Link How_to_quit}).
    
    If you are using  the @{" RESETHANDLER " Link RESETHANDLER} option, then  a reboot will  also
    save the time in the data  file, right before the actual reboot  takes
    place.
    
    When you  run SaveTime  again, the  clock  will get  set to  the  last
    written value, instead of whatever garbage it might contain, and  this
    is the whole idea of SaveTime.
    
    At any stage of the above procedure, SaveTime may display an error and
    exit. It may also just display  some information and keep on  running,
    if the  cause for  the  information is  not  fatal enough  to  require
    SaveTime to stop.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE How_to_quit "How to quit"
    
    If you want to quit SaveTime then you can use one of the several  ways
    we've provided. It's  entirely up to  you which one  to use. When  you
    send a SaveTime a quit signal, it will close the @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} window  (if
    it's opened) and  unload from  the memory  as quick  as possible.  The
    possibilities you have for quitting are:
    
    a) Run SaveTime twice
    If you start SaveTime and it  detects that a copy is already  running,
    it will NOT install itself. Instead it will pop up a requester  asking
    if you want to quit  the other one. In  any case will the second  copy
    never get installed  as it quits  itself when you've  answered to  the
    requester.
    
    b) SaveTime @{" QUIT " Link QUIT}
    You you -  from the Shell  - specify the  QUIT argument then  SaveTime
    will not even  pop up the  requester but just  signal another copy  to
    quit. This is a  little easier from  the Shell, as  you don't have  to
    grab the mouse. In the case  that no other SaveTime is running  you'll
    be told so and nothing will happen.
    
    c) SaveTimePrefs
    If you  use at  least Workbench  2.0  then you  can you  the  supplied
    SaveTimePrefs program to  quit an  already running  copy of  SaveTime.
    This is done  by clicking in  the 'Quit' gadget  of the  SaveTimePrefs
    window. You simply can't miss it :-).
    
    d) Other ^C signal
    In the  unlikely  event that  the  first three  possibilities  doesn't
    satisfy your needs, you can feel free to send SaveTime a ^C signal  by
    any other  means you  should know  of. I  will not  go into  a  deeper
    discussion here, as you probably already know the programs required if
    you want to use them.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Possible_problems "Possible problems"
    
    The following  is  a short  discussion  of the  possible  errors  that
    SaveTime can generate if it for some reason can't install itself.
    
    You can tell that  SaveTime installed properly if  it prints the  line
    'SaveTime 2.40 installed succesfully.'.  From Workbench you won't  get
    this message, but if you didn't get an error it probably worked.
    
    If you enter some wrong command  line arguments (from Shell), you  can
    instead get one of Commodore's (or ARP's if you're using Kickstart 1.2
    or 1.3)  error messages.  To be  honest, I  don't know  them all,  but
    examples are 'wrong number of arguments' and 'bad number'.
    
    When SaveTime  is started  from  Workbench it  checks the  tool  types
    instead of the command line arguments  and if it can't understand  one
    of them it will tell you so. Furthermore it will ignore that tool type
    and use the default value.
    
    If SaveTime is already running,  you'll be told so ('SaveTime  already
    running.') and will be  given the choice to  quit the already  running
    SaveTime.
    
    'SaveTime QUIT'  when no  SaveTime  is running  will print  'No  other
    SaveTime running.' and bring you back to the Shell prompt.
    
    'Can't create timer stuff.', 'Can't set time.' and other (can't)'s are
    more serious, but most probably they  are just signs of an  overloaded
    system.
    
    If SaveTime  can't  open  it's  datafile,  SaveTime  itself  will  NOT
    complain (but you  may get  a system  requester). This  goes both  for
    reading and writing of the data file. If SaveTime seems not to set the
    clock properly, try checking if it can write it's file (an error could
    be that you entered a non-existing path).
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Settings_file "Settings file"
    
    If you don't use at least Kickstart 2.0: Skip this section, you  don't
    have access to the goodies it  describes anyway. However, if you  have
    Kickstart 2.0+, do read on:
    
    Instead of having  the trouble  of entering arguments  on the  command
    line (for  the  Shell) or  as  tool  types (for  Workbench),  we  have
    provided a  method  of  specifying  them  through  a  Preferences-like
    program (the  program is  called @{" SaveTimePrefs " Link SaveTimePrefs}).  This program  will
    generate a file  containg your argument  specifications, and  SaveTime
    will automatically  read this  file when  it is  run. If  you  specify
    further arguments  (command line  or  tool types)  then they  will  be
    considered more important and therefore override the file generated by
    SaveTimePrefs.
    
    The benefit of using SaveTimePrefs is that it's easier, more intuitive
    and looks better than both the Shell and the tool type approach.
    
@{" Selecting settings file " Link Selecting_settings_file}
@{" Overriding the settings file " Link Overriding_the_settings_file}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Selecting_settings_file "Selecting settings file"
    
    By default,  SaveTime will  read  its default  arguments from  a  file
    called ENVARC:SaveTime.prefs. The settings  in SaveTimePrefs will  get
    saved to this file if you chose the 'Save' gadget. As you can probably
    see, this interacts nicely  and you actually don't  have to think  one
    bit about it (therefore  you can feel  free to skip  the rest of  this
    section :-).
    
    If, for some reason, you have  saved your setting somewhere else  (via
    the 'Save as...' menu item) then you might also want SaveTime to  read
    that file. This is  either done by setting  the 'default tool' of  the
    settings icon to SaveTime (see below) or by first single clicking  the
    settings icon, pressing  the shift  key and then  double clicking  the
    SaveTime icon.
    
    As SaveTimePrefs will  set the default  tool of the  settings file  to
    SaveTime, you just need to be certain that SaveTime is in the  default
    search path and then you can  double click the settings icon.  If  you
    want to change the default tool of the icon (if SaveTime is not in the
    default search  path)  then  you must  chose  'Information'  from  the
    'Icons' menu of Workbench, after single clicking on the settings  icon
    (this is the same  way as you enter tool  types, but please make  sure
    that you don't  get confused  and start  entering tool  types for  the
    settings. Tool types are for the  main SaveTime icon only!). When  the
    Information window opens  you should  easily find  the 'Default  tool'
    string gadget and here you enter  the full path for SaveTime. If  you,
    for example, have SaveTime in  the Utilities drawer of your  harddisk,
    which    is    called    MyHardDisk,    then    you    could     enter
    'MyHardDisk:Utilities/SaveTime' in the gadget.
    
    Once again: all this is actually quite redundant as SaveTime is  meant
    to be started  automatically and  therefore no such  things as  double
    clicking should ever  occur to  it. We've  mainly put  the ability  in
    because we wanted to make SaveTime look as much as a standard  utility
    as possible. All you should do is install SaveTime to start every time
    you reboot, select  your arguments in  SaveTimePrefs and let  SaveTime
    handle the rest.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Overriding_the_settings_file "Overriding the settings file"
    
    If both a settings file and  tool types or command line arguments  are
    found, then the later will count most (and therefore take effect). You
    can use this feature if you want slightly different settings just once
    and therefore don't  want to  alter the default  settings. However,  I
    don't see why you would ever want that.
    
    If you want to disable a  @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} or @{" RESETHANDLER " Link RESETHANDLER} argument in  the
    settings file then  you can set  their values to  zero. This will  cbe
    considered illegal and therefore the value  is ignored - but as it  IS
    specified, the argument in the settings file will also be ignored.
    

@ENDNODE

@NODE SaveTimePrefs "SaveTimePrefs"
    
    SaveTimePrefs is  the  Preferences  editor for  SaveTime  (and  should
    therefore get installed in your Prefs drawer), and is used for setting
    the default arguments (see @{" settings file " Link settings_file}).
    
    There really is very  little to say about  SaveTimePrefs; it's just  a
    graphical alternative to things described elsewhere and the design  of
    SaveTimePrefs fits  easily into  the standard  Preferences.  Therefore
    I'll just guide you very briefly through it:
    
@{" Menus " Link Menus}
@{" Gadgets " Link Gadgets}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Menus "Menus"
    
    'Project' menu:
    'Open...' and 'Save as...' loads respectively saves a set of arguments
    to a file you specify. A file  requester is used to ask what file  you
    want to  load/save  it from/to.  This  is  used if  you  want  several
    configurations of SaveTime lying around, but actually I don't see much
    reason why you should  want that. Most of  the time the 'Save'  gadget
    should be sufficient.
    
    'Quit' is like the 'Cancel' gadget - it stops without saving anything.
    
    'Edit' menu:
    'Reset To Defaults' will set the  gadgets to the values that  SaveTime
    uses as defaults. As SaveTime depends  a lot on your system, there  is
    not much need for this gadget either, actually - it just fits so  well
    into a Preferences editor :-).
    'Last Saved'  sets the  gadgets to  the state  they were  in when  the
    'Save' gadget  was  last  pressed.  This  is  identical  to  selecting
    'Open...' and then enter the file name as 'ENVARC:SaveTime.prefs'.  If
    you haven't saved anything since  you opened SaveTimePrefs, this  menu
    item will  -  naturally  - set  the  values  to what  they  were  when
    SaveTimePrefs was opened.
    
    'Settings' menu:
    'Create Icons?' is the only item here, and it toggles whether an  icon
    is created when you save the settings (either by the menu 'Save as...'
    or the gadget 'Save'). When  SaveTimePrefs is started from the  Shell,
    icons are by default NOT created, but if you start SaveTimePrefs  from
    Workbench they are. By using this item you can toggle this behaviour.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Gadgets "Gadgets"
    
    The two top  gadgets, 'Set time'  and 'Quit', are  only accessible  if
    SaveTime is running along with SaveTimePrefs. They are used to pop  up
    the @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} window and to quit the SaveTime that is running.
    
    The checkmark gadgets to the left are used for switching the different
    arguments on and  off. When an  argument is on,  a slider gadget  will
    allow you  to  specify  a  value (in  seconds)  that  goes  with  this
    argument.
    The 'File:' gadget shows the file selected by 'Select file...'. Due to
    the limited space, just  the file name is showed,  not the path -  but
    the path  does count.  To see  the  full path  you can  click  'Select
    file...'. The file name specifies where the data file of SaveTime (not
    the settings file) is saved (it's the @{" FILE " Link FILE} argument).
    Concerning the  actual meanings  of  the different  arguments,  please
    consult the @{" arguments " Link arguments} part.
    
    The  'Save'  gadget  will  save  the  settings  to  the  default  file
    'ENVARC:SaveTime.prefs', which is the file that SaveTime will load  if
    you don't tell it otherwise (see @{" Selecting settings file " Link Selecting_settings_file}).
    
    'Cancel' quits SaveTimePrefs without saving  the changes you may  have
    made.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Source_code "Source code"
    
    The source  (in C)  is  currently NOT  available  as Thomas  for  some
    obscure reason  thinks it  would  be better  if everybody  kept  their
    source codes to themselves.
    I, however, strongly point out that people can learn a lot from others
    sources, that people can fix a bug themselves only if they've got  the
    source and so on.
    However, to convience Thomas to  spread the source, I'm afraid  you'll
    have to write me a letter  telling that you'd prefer it if the  source
    was released. Then I can collect all the letters and show Thomas  what
    an excellent choice it would be.
    
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Credits_and_greetings "Credits and greetings"
     
     We have  created SaveTime  without much  help from  others -  simply
     because we haven't got much feed-back. We're therefore glad for  any
     response, and would like to thank a few people.
     
     First of all we  thank Simon Gramstrup for  his few suggestions  and
     comments (most major was the  @{" SETTIME " Link SETTIME} suggestion). Simon was  also
     able to discover a  bug that by some  kind of magic slipped  through
     our extensive testing and therefore  he is actually responsible  for
     version 2.30 turning into 2.31.
     
     Jřrgen Valentiner has  been helpful in  getting SaveTime around  the
     world; he was the guy who took care of hatching it into a world-wide
     file echo,  and is  also the  sysop of  the BBS  where both  of  the
     authors of SaveTime are points.
     Jřrgen will  always  carry the  most  recently released  version  of
     SaveTime. To call him, you may - just may - need these informations:
     
     The Amiga Zone, FidoNet 2:230/314, (+45) 32 52 42 94
                                        (+45) 32 50 87 30
                                        (+45) 32 46 13 40 (ISDNC)
     
     SaveTime is freq-able  for everybody under  the magic name  SAVETIME
     and is also  accessible if you  go on-line -  though you'll have  to
     search for the most current version, then.
     (Okay, end of commercials :-).
     
     Finaly we must  thank the  authors of DICE,  Yak, CycleToMenu,  csh,
     Snap, Reminder, ParNet, LhA, DiskSalv, DSound, SnoopDos, GoldED  and
     many, many other  programs that  has made  our everyday  use of  our
     Amigas so much more comfortable.
     The thing to note about these programs is that they are all  quality
     programs for almost  free (i.e.  at the  most ShareWare  with a  low
     registering price), and everybody using them or others of their like
     (including SaveTime :-) should consider sending a dollar or five  to
     the author even if he doesn't ask  for it. This way we can keep  the
     show going and still get top-quality for almost free in the future.
     
     
@ENDNODE

