@NODE Glossary "Glossary"
     
     For the ones  of you that  haven't got all  the experience with  the
     Amiga  that   we   do,   we'll  provide   you   with   this   little
     appendix/glossary.  The  goal  is  to  explain  enough  for  you  to
     understand, so if  you miss  some information  on something,  please
     tell us so we can add it.
     By the  way: most  likely you'll  have read  what you  want of  this
     appendix by following the link when you read the main guide.
     
@{" arp.library " Link arp.library}
@{" LIBS " Link LIBS}
@{" Installer " Link Installer}
@ENDNODE

@NODE arp.library "arp.library"
     
     ARP (AmigaDos Replacement Project) was very popular in the 1.3  days
     of the Kickstart, as it  extended the Kickstart with some  functions
     that took a great workload off the programmers of other software. As
     Kickstart 2.0  was  introduced, the  need  for ARP  disappeared  (as
     Kickstart 2.0 has identical features),  and the last release of  ARP
     was in 1989.
     The heart  of ARP  is a  file called  'arp.library', which  must  be
     installed in your @{" LIBS " Link LIBS} drawer -  but only if you want to use  ARP,
     of course.
     
     To use SaveTime with Kickstart 1.2  or 1.3, you DO need  arp.library
     (version 39, also  called release 1.3).  If you don't  have it,  you
     might have a slight problem as  ARP is getting harder to find  these
     days (it's not even on a Fish Disk). Once you find it,  installation
     information should be  with it,  so we  won't go  into details  here
     (also because most people either already  have ARP or don't want  it
     at all).
     
     We suggest  that  instead of  starting  a  search for  ARP  you  get
     yourself a  proper Kickstart;  today you  can't do  much without  at
     least Kickstart 2.0 - and tomorrow you can do even less  (relatively
     - of course your programs won't suddenly stop working :-).
     The need for  2.0 Kickstart is  not because of  SaveTime - it  works
     without, only with a  few functions disabled  (things that can't  be
     done with Kickstart 1.3). However, we have decided that version 2.40
     of SaveTime is the  last version which  will support Kickstart  1.3.
     The reason for this is that it is quite annoying to have double code
     in the source; one for Kickstart 1.3 and one for 2.0+.
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE LIBS "LIBS"
     
     The LIBS: drawer is a drawer  named LIBS on the disk you boot  with.
     That is, to  have something  installed 'in the  LIBS: drawer'  (e.g.
     'arp.library') it  must  be  in  this drawer.  It  is  important  to
     remember that even  if you  change disk  a million  times, LIBS:  is
     still pointing to the drawer named LIBS on the *boot* disk.
     (The boot disk is the first disk the Amiga reads after a restart. If
     you've got a harddisk, this will most likely be it).
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installer "Installer"
     
     Installer is a program to install other products. It's bundled  with
     all Workbenches since  version 2.1  but is also  released as  Public
     Domain by Commodore-Amiga.
     
     The flexibilty and availability of Installer, combined with its user
     friendliness both to the programmer  of the installation script  and
     the one who's actually installing something have made Installer very
     popular.
     
     But, hey - why don't you just try it out? :-)
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE History "History"

     Below is a description of what  has changed in the various  versions
     of SaveTime that have  been. Each link  describes what changed  with
     that particular version.
     
     
@{" Version 2.40 (30-Apr-94) " Link Version_2.40_(30-Apr-94)}
@{" Version 2.31 (23-Jul-93) " Link Version_2.31_(23-Jul-93)}
@{" Version 2.30 (23-Jul-92) " Link Version_2.30_(23-Jul-92)}
@{" Version 2.20 (03-Jun-93) " Link Version_2.20_(03-Jun-93)}
@{" Version 2.1 (07-Apr-93) " Link Version_2.1_(07-Apr-93)}
@{" Version 2.00 (21-Mar-93) " Link Version_2.00_(21-Mar-93)}
@{" Version 1.1 (26-Feb-93) " Link Version_1.1_(26-Feb-93)}
@{" Version 1.0 (18-Feb-93) " Link Version_1.0_(18-Feb-93)}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.40_(30-Apr-94) "Version 2.40 (30-Apr-94)"

     Not detaching from the Shell (which was an unsafe idea anyway).
     Improved the SETTIME window
      - Gadgets auto repeat.
      - Passing midnight (using arrow gadgets) will change the date.
      - Asyncronous; you can now quit SaveTime even with the window open.
      - The window will pop up on ^D signal (used by SaveTimePrefs).
     Reset handler added.
     Workbench support added.
     Extended (human readable :-) Shell help.
     Prefs program/Config file.
     Manual in .guide format.
     Last 1.2/1.3 compatible version.
     Installer script.
     
     File: 9788. Mem: around 13000 (WB) / 19000 (Shell+Run).
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.31_(23-Jul-93) "Version 2.31 (23-Jul-93)"

     "Tiny" bug fix from V2.30. Gadget  images did not show correctly  on
     Amigas with fast memory free. This is now hopefully fixed.
     (Tech: the Image struct was placed in chip mem instead of the actual
     images). Thanks to Simon Gramstrup for reporting this so quickly. 
     
     File and memory usage remains the same as in version 2.30.
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.30_(23-Jul-92) "Version 2.30 (23-Jul-92)"

     This is the first version from SaveTime<tm> Development, Inc.  which
     Anders and I have  formed together. Therefore  this version has  all
     the features from both  his and mine  versions, plus the  following:
     SaveTime has now both manual and automatical time correction, for  a
     more precise clock.
     
     File: 7080 bytes. Mem: 9144.
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.20_(03-Jun-93) "Version 2.20 (03-Jun-93)"

     Anders Melchiorsen's  second version  of  SaveTime. Like  the  other
     version from  Anders,  it can't  run  at KS1.3.  But  it has  a  few
     advantages: It offers several ways to quit. It can't execute, if  it
     is already running. Help option. Better error handling.
     
     File: 2912 bytes. Mem: 5328 bytes. (Unreleased).
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.1_(07-Apr-93) "Version 2.1 (07-Apr-93)"

     SaveTime is now  autodetaching. This means  that SaveTime uses  less
     ram, and you  can make an  'EndCLI' even when  SaveTime is  running.
     (My) SaveTime don't need c:date anymore. It uses the 'SetSystemTime'
     routine from  Anders Melchiorsen's  version  2.00. This  version  is
     bigger than version 2.00, but it uses less ram.
     
     File: 5848 bytes, Mem: 8136.
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_2.00_(21-Mar-93) "Version 2.00 (21-Mar-93)"

     Anders Melchiorsen's version of SaveTime, which made the same as  my
     version 1.1,  only smaller,  and it  didn't need  c:date (and  under
     KS1.2/1.3 c:run ), but 2.00 could not run under KS1.2/1.3.
     
     File: 1496 bytes, Mem: 9888 bytes. (Unrealeased).
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_1.1_(26-Feb-93) "Version 1.1 (26-Feb-93)"

     You can  now choose  how  many seconds  you  want SaveTime  to  wait
     between two saves. It is much smaller, and needs less memory.
     
     File: 5424 bytes, Mem: 20000 bytes.
     
@ENDNODE

@NODE Version_1.0_(18-Feb-93) "Version 1.0 (18-Feb-93)"

     This is the first version.
     
     File: 8208 bytes, Mem: 22640 bytes.
     



@ENDNODE

